Title: Can the new aid-growth models be replicated
Author-Name: Jensen, Peter Sandholt
Author-Name: Paldam, Martin
Author-Email: psjensen@econ.au.dk
Author-WorkPlace-Name: Department of Economics Aarhus, Denmark
Author-WorkPlace-Postal: 8000 Aarhus C, Denmark
Author-WorkPlace-Fax: +45 86 13 63 34
Abstract: The recent literature on the aid-growth relation discusses two competing models: The Good
Policy Model, where the key feature is policy times aid, and the Medicine Model, where the key
feature is aid squared. Both have been reached on a sample of about 1/3 of the available data. We
present a base model, to replicate both models on that data set. It is then replicated on as much
of the available data as possible. Within the sample the Good Policy Model proves fragile, while
the Medicine Model is more robust. Neither model replicates outside the original data sample.
Further, we apply a semi-parametric regression technique to test for an unknown functional form
of the aid-growth relation. It rejects that aid is statistically significant. Thus the evidence in favor
of an aid-growth relationship - let alone a nonlinear one - is weak.
Classification-JEL: C14, C23, F35, O4
Keywords: Aid effectiveness, growth, semi-parametric panel regression
Length: 22
